      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blueberries indeed thrive in acidic soils, typically with a pH between 4.0 and 5.5. In acidic soils, iron is more readily available due to its high solubility. However, if the pH becomes too high, iron initially becomes less soluble, but then it precipitates out of solution as iron oxides, particularly goethite and limonite, in the form of hydrated iron oxides. These compounds can bind to organic matter and make iron less accessible to the roots, effectively \"locking it in\" the soil.",
